            . I live in <placeName id="t18090920-162-crimeloc952">Crispin street. Spitalfields</placeName>
                  <interp inst="t18090920-162-crimeloc952" type="placeName" value="Crispin street. Spitalfields"></interp>
                  <interp inst="t18090920-162-crimeloc952" type="type" value="crimeLocation"></interp>
                  <join result="offencePlace" targOrder="Y" targets="t18090920-162-off950 t18090920-162-crimeloc952"></join>. I lost the copper on the 30th of June, I had suspicion of the prisoner, knowing that he had no money, he lodged in the house, he got drunk that evening, and bought ham and beef, on the next morning I missed a silver spoon, he owned taking the table spoon before the magistrate.</p>
               <p>Q. What is the prisoner - A. A <rs id="t18090920-162-deflabel953" type="occupation">butcher</rs>
                  <join result="persNameOccupation" targOrder="Y" targets="t18090920-162-defend1561 t18090920-162-deflabel953"></join>, he had lodged with me about eight or nine months.</p>
               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t18090920-162-person1565">
                  THOMAS 
                  HART
               <interp inst="t18090920-162-person1565" type="surname" value="HART"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18090920-162-person1565" type="given" value="THOMAS"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18090920-162-person1565" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
            . I took the prisoner in custody on the next morning, he told me he had sold the silver spoon to Smouchee, in Petticoat-lane, for five shillings.</p>
               <p>Prisoner's Defence. There were seven or eight young men in the house, I had half a guinea, I spent it, and got drunk in his house, on the next day he said I had robbed him; I know nothing about it.</p>
               <p>
                  <rs id="t18090920-162-verdict954" type="verdictDescription">
